{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472386"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1299"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.93,0.02,0.05,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103249"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1299"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"370"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103249"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department at 2:00am with a four-day history of runny nose and mild cough. Tonight he woke suddenly with a harsh barking cough and noisy breathing. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has not received any routine childhood immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with audible inspiratory stridor and increased work of breathing. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Croup","Bacterial tracheitis","Acute epiglottitis","Inhaled foreign body","Retropharyngeal abscess"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecroup\u003C/strong\u003E (laryngotracheobronchitis), including the characteristic barking cough and stridor following several days of upper respiratory symptoms. The nocturnal onset is also typical, as croup symptoms often worsen at night. The presentation with a prodrome of upper respiratory symptoms followed by sudden onset of stridor and barking cough is the classic pattern for viral croup.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial tracheitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with high fever, toxic appearance, and copious purulent secretions. While it can complicate viral croup, the child is not toxic enough for this diagnosis. Bacterial tracheitis usually occurs after initial improvement of viral croup with subsequent deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute epiglottitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in an unimmunised child. However, epiglottitis typically presents with rapid onset of high fever, marked toxicity, and muffled voice (\u0027hot potato voice\u0027). The presence of cough and the longer prodrome make this less likely. Children with epiglottitis often sit forward in a tripod position and appear severely ill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhaled foreign body\u003C/strong\u003E typically has a sudden onset with a choking episode, though this history may be absent. The preceding upper respiratory symptoms make this less likely to be the primary diagnosis. Foreign body aspiration usually lacks the prodromal symptoms seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetropharyngeal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with fever, neck pain and stiffness, and dysphagia. While it can cause stridor, the presence of cough and coryzal symptoms makes croup more likely. Retropharyngeal abscess typically develops over several days and may follow pharyngeal trauma or infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of croup includes oral dexamethasone and observation. More severe cases may require nebulised adrenaline. Any deterioration or failure to improve should prompt consideration of alternative diagnoses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Croup typically presents with barking cough and stridor after several days of upper respiratory symptoms.","Nocturnal onset of symptoms is characteristic of croup, with symptoms often worsening at night.","Unimmunised children are at higher risk of vaccine-preventable causes of stridor such as epiglottitis."],"references":["Boudewyns A, Claes J, Van de Heyning P. Clinical practice: an approach to stridor in infants and children. Eur J Pediatr. 2010 Feb;169(2):135-41. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19763619/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T21:13:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T21:15:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1299"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"